title.value: Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 069: Gregory the Great, Homiliae XL in euangelia

note.value: The initials are of rather rough execution. A peculiar feature is that every page is bordered on R. and L. and between the columns with lines of red dots, in groups of three.
The hand varies in closeness but may very probably be the same throughout.

CCCC MS 69, containing Gregory the Great's Forty Homilies on the Gospels, was written in Insular Hybrid minuscule and decorated in typical Insular fashion with red dots, interlace, and occasional animal heads. It was probably made in England south of the Humber, dating to the early part of the early ninth century, and is as such a relatively late product of the Insular book-producing tradition in England, which was to be greatly disrupted by Viking attacks of the middle of the ninth century. note.value: The Gospel Lections are given in full
Omelia euangeliorum gregorii papae urbis romae numero uiginti. secundum marcum
In illo tempore maria magdalene et maria iacobi et solomae
Initial I, in green, pink and yellow, with panels of interlaced work. The ground round it is thickly dotted with red. The letters "N ILLO" are filled in with pink and interlacing.
The Homilies are irregularly numbered: the last, imperfect, should be the xlth (on Dives and Lazarus).
